engineering that often do not have a claim to economic theory or practice, yet nonetheless dictate forms of economic activity. Contributing to economic anthropology, science and technology studies, energy studies, and the anthropology of expertise, this book is a map of the everyday infrastructures of economy and energy into which we are plugged as denizens of a technological world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aEconomic anthropologyzUnited States. 0aElectric utilitiesxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aElectric utilitieszUnited States. 0aElectric utilities-United States. 0aExpertisexEconomic aspectszUnited States. 0aExpertise-Economic aspects-United States. 0aMarketsxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aMarkets-Social aspects-United States. 0aTechnologyxEconomic aspectszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aderegulation.  aeconomic anthropology.  aeconomics.  aelectric grid.  aelectricity.  aengineering.  ainfrastructure.  amarkets.  arestructuring.  athe United States.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073914540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362822940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503628229423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503628229/original  a978-3-11-073914-5  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles